    excerpt: "Unlike paid ads that stop when you stop paying, great content keeps generating traffic for years. Here's the strategy behind building a content engine that compounds over time.",
    content: `
      <h2>The Compounding Nature of Content Marketing</h2>
      <p>A well-written blog post published today will still be generating organic traffic three years from now. This compounding effect is what makes content marketing one of the highest long-term ROI investments a business can make.</p>

      <h2>Building Your Content Strategy Around Search Demand</h2>
      <p>Effective content marketing starts with understanding what your potential customers are searching for. Keyword research tools reveal not just search volume but the questions, concerns, and comparisons your audience is making.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Target a mix of informational, comparison, and buying-intent keywords</li>
        <li>Focus on long-tail keywords where competition is lower</li>
        <li>Build topical depth before breadth</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Content Pyramid Framework</h2>
      <p>Structure your content around a pyramid: a few comprehensive pillar pages at the top covering broad topics (2,000+ words), supported by dozens of cluster articles addressing specific subtopics, all internally linked together to pass authority.</p>

      <h2>Content Formats That Drive Engagement</h2>
      <p>Different formats serve different purposes. Long-form guides for SEO. Short-form articles for social sharing. Video content for complex concepts. Infographics for data. Case studies for conversion. Use the right format for each audience need.</p>

      <h2>The Editorial Process That Ensures Quality</h2>
      <p>Quality over quantity is not a cliché — it's the core principle of effective content marketing. Every piece should demonstrate genuine expertise, answer the searcher's question completely, and provide value beyond what's already available.</p>

      <h2>Promotion and Distribution</h2>
      <p>Even great content needs a distribution strategy. Share on relevant social platforms. Reach out to industry publications for content placements. Build an email list that delivers your best content directly to interested readers.</p>

      <h2>Measuring Content Performance</h2>
      <p>Track organic sessions, average position in Search Console, time on page, scroll depth, and assisted conversions. These metrics reveal which content is genuinely useful versus which merely exists.</p>

      <h2>Content Refreshes: The Overlooked Growth Lever</h2>
      <p>Regularly updating top-performing content with fresh data, examples, and sections can revive declining rankings and extend the useful life of your best assets. Schedule quarterly content audits.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>Content marketing rewards patience and consistency. Businesses that commit to a long-term content strategy consistently build the most valuable and durable organic traffic assets online.</p>
    `,
